    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "nitrogen deficiency? okay i think i've heard of that. how do i actually fix it though? like what should i add to the soil to get the levels back up, and do i need to worry about the pH levels too?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A nitrogen deficiency is usually best tackled by giving your tomatoes a good, steady dose of nitrogen, which is what makes those leaves green and vibrant, not sickly like a goblin who's been eating only moldy mushrooms. You could try adding a balanced, slow-release fertilizer, or if you want a quick fix, a liquid fertilizer rich in nitrogen. It's a good idea to follow the instructions on the package, because you don't want to overfeed them, which is like giving a goblin too many shiny trinkets—they might just hoard them and get grumpy!\n\nAs for pH, yes, you should definitely keep an eye on it! The soil's pH level is crucial because it dictates how well your tomato plants can actually *absorb* those nutrients, even if they are right there in the soil. If the pH is too high or too low, it's like putting a treasure chest full of gold in a swamp—the goblins can't get to it! You can test your soil to see what it is, and then use lime or sulfur, depending on the reading, to adjust it.",
