    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that's a bit of a weird comparison lol. but okay, so if the pH is off, how do i know if it's too high or too low? do i just buy a kit? and what happens if the plants can't absorb the nutrients?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A proper soil test kit is usually the most reliable way to know if your pH is too high or too low, though some digital meters can give you a rough idea. You'll typically get a reading on a scale, and you want your tomatoes to be happy in a slightly acidic to neutral range, usually between 6.0 and 6.8. If the pH is too high, it's like the soil is too dry and dusty for the little goblin to find any tasty roots; if it's too low, it can become too acidic, which is like a swampy bog where the good nutrients get locked up.\n\nIf your plants can't absorb the nutrients, even if you've added the best fertilizer, they will still suffer, just like a goblin who has the map to the treasure but can't find the right path to the chest! The nutrients are there, but the plant is effectively starving because the chemical balance in the soil is wrong. This is why checking the pH first is so important—it's the gatekeeper to all the good stuff.",
